metadata.name: Wood Generation v1.0 #3
metadata.description:
This entire project will be free for all to mint until it is gone. I'm exploring the idea of creating simulated wood of many different types, colors, and grains. The goal is to allow generation of "boards" which look like they are separate cuts from the same tree. Thus the grain from one must be related to the next but must not be identical...

In this experiment, I slice 9 boards and line them up left-to-right to see the similarities. The features will list the approximate parameters driving the generator.

If the experiment is successful, the code will be able to make as many slices needed, at any thickness, in any direction (across or with the grain, or at any angle).

Enjoy! Feel free to look me up on Discord (Vroomcrds#4688) and DM me if you have questions or suggestions!

All secondary revenues will be shared equally with the minter, THREE.js and Girls Who Code.

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle
Right click and drag to change the view center
Mouse wheel to change the distance to the view center

metadata.name: De/Frag #510
metadata.description:
De/Frag is an homage to a classic algorithm in early computer art: Flood Fill. As a teenager in the late '80s, and without any literature, I spent weeks implementing a version for my very own drawing program for the Atari XL. It was the first non-trivial (to me) algorithm which made me want to learn more about data structures, the concept of recursion, divide-and-conquer...

Even though Flood Fill was available in most commercial drawing & office apps of the time, I gained a deep appreciation of the algorithm by building it from scratch myself. 30+ years later I know its aesthetic possibilities are still far from exhausted. This is an invitation for re-exploration by others too!

As with many design algorithms, my primary interest isn't even the final result, but observing the inner workings. I massively slowed down and time-sliced the process for this piece. I do recommend giving each of these unique versions some time to allow them to evolve their ever-changing patterns (Note: each piece never loops!).

metadata.name: Terra-Bytes #176
metadata.description:
Terra-bytes is a generative art project of landscapes sculpted in virtual reality.

The work is composed of more than 10 different types of landscapes, each divided into 5 layers of depth that are mixed together generating millions of possible combinations.
In addition, these landscapes are accompanied by different characters, objects and elements that give life and complexity to each generated scene, making it unique.
Each visual element of this work was sculpted in VR with virtual hands and then exported to Blender for post processing and rendering.

Many thanks to @Purespider for the template.
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.name: play/plaque #341
metadata.description:
A grid of trailing shapes. Each shape in the line wants to be like the shape in front of it.

The traits
4 shapes: square, cross, triangle, circle
5 grid sizes 1->5 with 1x1 grids being rarest (5%)
2 fill styles: hollow (80%, crosses can't be hollow) and filled (20%)
20% chance for all shapes to be the same
6 color palettes:
- Coffee and Blueberry
- Tropicana
- Monochrome
- Spectrum
- Peach and Pear
- Goji and Kelp

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao)
